  "exemplar_id": "ex_pericarditis_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "39-year-old male presenting with 8 hours of sharp, constant left-sided chest pain rated 7-8/10, with associated shortness of breath, lightheadedness, and palpitations. Pain began the prior evening after moving furniture, though he denies feeling injured at the time. He has a significant family history (father had MI at 45) and is a 10-15 pack-year smoker. The doctor has established the pain is sharp (not crushing/pressure), non-radiating, and constant.",
  "good_next_question": "OK, so do you find laying down makes the pain worse?",
  "rationale": "This question tests for the positional/pleuritic character that distinguishes pericarditis from acute coronary syndrome — the two leading differentials in a young man with sharp constant chest pain and cardiac risk factors. The patient has already volunteered that 'not laying down helps,' so the doctor is anchoring this critical feature explicitly before moving on. Positional pain worse when supine and relieved sitting forward is highly specific for pericarditis, while ACS pain is classically unaffected by position. A confirmed positive substantially raises pericarditis probability and reframes the workup toward ECG looking for diffuse ST elevation/PR depression and an echo for effusion, rather than the trop/cath pathway. Asking this beats jumping straight to risk-factor questions because it changes which diagnosis is being worked up.",
  "tags": [
